CMPINF 2100 Week 07

Reshaping from WIDE to LONG via melt

We have seen how to explore data. Focusing on the RELATIONSHIPS between continuous variables this week.

We have also continued to see how important it is to GROUP BY or CONDITION on categorical variables.

There is an important DATA MANIPULATION task that will further help us use GROUPING to visually explore our data!

Import Modules

Motivate why we need this operation

We know how to look at a marginal distribution for a SINGLE variable.

In[8]:
sns.displot(data=penguins, x="flipper_length_mm", kind="hist", bins=11)

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

But to visualize every continuous variable histogram...we need to call a lot of functions!!!

We need to iterate over all the continuous columns!!

You might think we can use a for-loop, but you are WRONG!!!

Instead...we want to use a simple line of code to show ALL continuous variable MARGINAL distributions in one figure!!

In[9]:
penguins.hist()

plt.show()

But what if I don't want to use Pandas? And I want to use Seaborn?

What happens if we use the same style of syntax for Seaborn as we did with Pandas?

In[10]:
sns.displot(data=penguins, kind="hist", aspect=2)

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

Lets use a similar syntax to make a BOXPLOT!!

In[11]:
sns.catplot(data=penguins, kind="box", aspect=2)

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

The SCALE is completely dominated by a single column or variable. Thats why we cannot see the histograms for all variables!!

Instead, we want Seaborn to create separate facets for each column just as Pandas did.

But Seaborn likes data in LONG FORMAT and Pandas likes data in WIDE FORMAT.

Lets excute RESHAPING from WIDE to LONG format to see what long format does!!!

Long Format

Lets begin by focusing on JUST the numeric columns. Lets separate them out.

In[12]:
penguins_features = penguins.select_dtypes("number").copy()

To STACK or GATHER all 4 columns in the CURRENT WIDE FORMAT into LONG FORMAT...we need to MELT the data.

RESHAPING from WIDE to LONG is accomplished with the .melt method.

In[14]:
penguins_features.melt()

By default, we LOSE the original .index attribute when we MELT. Meaning we lose which row the data originally came from!!

We can KEEP the original .index by setting the ignore_index argument to False!!

In[21]:
penguins_features.melt(ignore_index=False)
Out[21]:

0 body_mass_g 3750.0

I prefer to CONVERT the .index attribute into a REGULAR columns and RENAME it to rowid.

HOWEVER we cannot melt with the default arguments!!

We do not want to GATHER or STACK the rowid column with the other variables!!

Instead, we need to specify the rowid column uniquely DEFINES the ROW ID!!

In[27]:
penguins_features.reset_index().rename(columns={'index': 'rowid'}).melt(id_vars=["rowid"])
Out[27]:
rowid variable value

1 1 bill_length_mm 39.5

In[31]:
penguins_objects = penguins.select_dtypes("object").copy()

Lets define a list that contains the rowid col and the 3 object col names!!

This list will therefore hold ALL cols that uniquely define the ROW!

In[34]:
id_cols = ["rowid"] + penguins_objects.columns.to_list()
In[35]:
id_cols
Out[35]:
['rowid', 'species', 'island', 'sex']

We can use id_cols to identify the columns to NOT gather or STACK when we call .melt() method on the original data set!!

Plotting with Long Format

We can now associate the variable column with FACETS in Seaborn!!!

Lets call the sns.displot() function again but this time with the LONG FORMAT data and assigning col to variable.

In[50]:
sns.displot(data=penguins_lf, x="value", col="variable", kind="hist")

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

We need to force FREE or NOT SHARING x and y axis scales!!

In[52]:
sns.displot(data=penguins_lf, x="value", col="variable", kind="hist", 
           facet_kws={"sharex":False, "sharey":False})

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

One more change..by default the histograms want to use the common bins in all facets!!!

In[53]:
sns.displot(data=penguins_lf, x="value", col="variable", kind="hist", 
           facet_kws={"sharex":False, "sharey":False}, 
           common_bins=False)

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

We can do the same thing with KDE...but common norm must be FALSE!!!

In[57]:
sns.displot(data=penguins_lf, x="value", col="variable", kind="kde", 
           facet_kws={"sharex":False, "sharey":False}, common_norm=False)

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

Why is the LONG FORMAT so usefull?

Because we can easily group by cat variable!!

We can group each FACET by a cat variable to study the CONDITIONAL DISTRIBUTION for each numeric column!!

In[59]:
sns.displot(data=penguins_lf, x="value", col="variable", kind="kde", 
            hue="species",
           facet_kws={"sharex":False, "sharey":False}, common_norm=False)

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

We have reshaped...and we have kept ALL non-numeric cols...we can FACET by other variables!!!

In[60]:
sns.displot(data=penguins_lf, x="value", col="variable", kind="kde", 
            row="species", hue="sex",
            facet_kws={"sharex":False, "sharey":False}, common_norm=False)

plt.show()

/Applications/anaconda3/envs/cmpinf2100/lib/python3.8/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:123: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

We can use OTHER types of PLOTS from the LONG format without changing anything!!!

We can show the CONDITIONAL distributions for each numeric col groupy by species as boxplots!!

In[68]:
sns.catplot(data=penguins_lf, x="species", y="value", col="variable", kind="box", hue="species", sharey=False, col_wrap=2)

plt.show()

We can include an additional grouping via the box hue. So let's examine the differences between Male and Female as the hue.

In[69]:
sns.catplot(data=penguins_lf, x="species", y="value", col="variable", kind="box", hue="sex", sharey=False, col_wrap=2)

plt.show()
